title: Aust bonds weaken for a second day
text:
Wed, Jul 29, 2015, 4:58 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed Aust bonds weaken for a second day AAP â€“ 15 minutes ago Print 
Australian bond futures prices are down for a second day as equity markets strengthen and as traders wait for the outcome of the US Federal Reserve's two day policy meeting. 
CMC Markets strategist Michael McCarthy said investors are moving out of safe haven assets because of a return of confidence in financial markets. 
"We did see this movement in Europe and the US overnight as concerns about the outlook for China appeared to take a U-turn and that has been weighing on bond markets," he said. 
Mr McCarthy said that the bond market is also playing it safe ahead of an announcement by the US central bank's Federal Open Market Committee, early on Thursday morning, Australian time. 
"This one's been pretty well flagged, there's a clear consensus there will be no change in interest rates," he said. 
"There is some thought around the timing of subsequent rate rises in the US, with a focus on a much gentler lifting scenario." 
At 1630 AEST on Wednesday, the September 2015 10-year bond futures contract was trading at 97.170 (implying a yield of 2.830 per cent), down from 97.205 (2.795 per cent) on Tuesday. 
The September 2015 three-year bond futures contract was at 98.100 (1.900 per cent), down from 98.110 (1.890 per cent). 
KEY MOVEMENTS: 
* CGS 5.5pct Jan 2018, 1.861%, from 1.853% on Tuesday 
* CGS 4.25pct April 2026, 2.877%, from 2.845% 
Sydney Futures Exchange prices: 
* September 2015 bill futures, 97.920. unchanged 
* December 2015 bill futures, 97.980, unchanged 
(*Closes taken at 1630 AEST previous local session)
